english:
  title: Inscription on the Angbu Sundial
  author: Kim Don
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In all our undertakings,
    Nothing surpasses the knowledge of time.
    At night, the water clock marks the hours,
    But the day keeps its secrets.
    So I cast copper into a vessel,
    Its form like a cauldron,
    With a gnomon pointing true,
    North meeting South face to face.
    The shadow traces its hidden path,
    Each point marked with care—
    Inside, the degrees are drawn,
    Half the turning wheel of heaven.
    The divine figure carved within
    Serves those simple folk
    Who cannot read the sky.
    The marks grow clear and bright
    Where sunlight breaks through,
    Placed by the roadside
    Where crowds might gather and see.
    From this beginning,
    Our people shall know when to rise and work.
  footnotes:
    - The Angbu Sundial (앙부일구) was an important astronomical instrument created during the Joseon dynasty to help common people tell time during daylight hours. The 'water clock' (경루) refers to the clepsydra, used for measuring time at night. The 'divine figure' likely refers to astronomical or mythological imagery that would have decorated the instrument.
